metadata.name: Monochrome Intersections #38
metadata.description:
I decided to do this version because Intersections created too many issues with the previews. I made a reserve list for all collectors of Intersections (this reserve list will be available during 1 week). I put a small price because of preview‚Äôs issues and I am really grateful to saw all my projects found collectors, and I don‚Äôt know how to tell you üôè
‚Ä®I also worked on a bug to fix the rendering on objkt.com.‚Ä®

Monochrome Intersections are a group of artworks creating organic and animated lines. A mix between digital renderings with colorful lines and a generated grid creating a paper-like visual.

Lines are animated with an infinite algorithm to create a mesmerizing animation. 
The pieces's size, position and frequency are generated for each token, along with the colour theme and the composition effect. 

You can click to play/pause the animation.

Features :
- Clip: triangle, circle or reversed triangle
- LinesCount: number of lines
- smallLines: boolean, if lines are thin or bold
- colorTheme: name of the color theme
- filter: Canvas composition effect applied : difference, multiply, xor, hard-light, source-over
- isDistorted: distortions enabled

‚Ä®Handmade by code with Javascript, made with fragment.tools
Quentin Hocd√©, Brussels (Belgium), 2023.

metadata.name: CSS Molecules #66
metadata.description:
This 3d animated work is composed almost completely of HTML + CSS. There is a limited amount of javascript to construct the scene and facilitate interactive controls. üö´ <canvas>!

A bit of history about this approach: As my first coding language HTML and CSS holds a special place in my heart. Even when I jumped into 3D my first creations were made with just some html + css coded in notepad. Earlier this year I took this idea to the next level with a yet-to-be-released 3D bedrooms project, filling it with objects and ever-refining my scene construction practice. This system for scene construction became the basis for a few other generative projects here on fxhash under my pseudonym htmlcss.tez. Here I abandon my usual representational focus with this technique and dive right into the abstract.

metadata.name: Caught in the maelstrom #116
metadata.description:
An ever-growing vortex consisting of lots of different mesh lines that move in unison.

Clicking the canvas will trigger a boost in speed and line size, and produce a random chord by the main synth.

Holding down your pointer will reverse the vortex and play an additional synth on release. Double tapping will have the same effect audio-wise.

This is part of the celebration of fxhash turning 1. That‚Äôs why there are 365 editions, and 50% of all primary sales will be donated evenly between ‚ÄúProcessing Foundation‚Äù and ‚ÄúThree.js‚Äù. 20% of all royalties are given back to the minter.

Here are some stats for you:

About 1/10 will render the lines in wireframes.
There are 2 different synth pitches distributed evenly.
10% will have one single line color, instead of 3 primary ones.
In rough measures, every 4th will have an irregular wiggle motion flow instead of a circular one.

In addition to all of the above, there can be different values in regards to line counts, line lengths, line widths, speeds, width grows, radius increments, angle increments, z-index increments, background colors, border colors, and so on.

#fxhashturnsone

@computeremotions - 2022-11-13

metadata.name: Floating Orbs #3
metadata.description: This abstract artwork, Floating Orbs, was created to symbolize the many objects floating around in space. Each artwork is layered images of floating orbs. The compiled images represent imagined pathways of objects floating around in space. The images are intended to inspire a feeling of movement and floating in the viewer. As well, as to spur thought about the impact man's actions have on outer space.

metadata.name: A Bugged Forest #80
metadata.description:
A forest has stories to tell.
About times that were, about times that will be.
-
This project was minted in much unusual conditions. 
We gathered here, by 38 degrees heat. We belong to a crowd who loves stories, of civilisations at stake and deities, of afterlife and worship. We drank and hugged and chanted pagan hymns. We minted the Bugged Forest from our place on earth that we call Hell just for the fun of it. We are passionate, and loving, and angry and desperate. We, people of the soil, under a bugged sun.
-
This project is the long-form version of an algorithm that contains a bug. ‚ÄúThe Bugged Tree‚Äù‚Äôs code was salvaged and stored and served as the core motivation and engine for an entire forest. Its concept is about releasing the control. I am a  byproduct of evolution, an iteration of that specie who wanted utter control, and which at some point, lost control over its own creation. As a generative artist, I chose to welcome the event of chance into my creative process. The symbolism in chance made me feel humble and free. Unwilling to make any change to a story that the Tree needed to tell me, as a listener, rather than a writer of my own idealised fantasies.
-
The iterations aren‚Äôt under control. They may be odd and off. We have to accept it. They are also plottable, press [s] in live mode to get a SVG. Attempt the plot at your own risk, as there‚Äôs a possibility for it to come near to impossibilities or cause paper or motor damage, and most certainly, a bugged drawing.
-
From Earth or from Hell, with love, yours truthfully, NFTBiker and zancan

metadata.name: Action; System #8
metadata.description:
Action; system is an experimental study inspired by the work of Fran√ßois Morellet. Morellet was one of the founders of the Groupe de Recherche d'Art Visuel (GRAV), founded in the 60s. His work was often informed by systems, a set of rules that determine the artwork, reducing the artist's subjectivity to a minimum.

This work explores what happens when we let go of the strict rule set. Do we ever fully let go?

-----------------
This work was released for the 2023 fundraising exhibition Cure3, and all of the proceeds and 1% of royalties will go to Parkinson's research funds. You can find more information at https://cure3.co.uk/.

-----------------
Controls
- R: new randomized output (the chances of recovering one of these outputs are very slim, that's what the next control is for)
- E: high-res output
- Double click: fullscreen

While you see the eye of Horus, your artwork is loading.

------------------
Made with p5.js & glsl

metadata.name: Cave Etchings #102
metadata.description:
Cave Etchings are detailed line drawings generated from unedited AI images of caves, conjoining an AI process with a generative art process. The project is not just an exercise in aesthetics, it is about seeing things the way a computer 'sees'. The original AI cave series focused on how AI Computer Vision can imagine fantastical caves; in cave etchings, the software visualises pixel data as movement, rotating lines according to hue, saturation, and brightness values. The project is inspired by the artwork of Franklin Booth (1874- 1948).
More details here: https://www.plummerfernandez.com/works/cave-etchings/

Instructions:
‚Äòs‚Äô to save
‚Äòh‚Äô to save hi-res version (may look slightly different in viewport as the moir√© effect can vary)
‚Äòt‚Äô to download a thank you message
